# React & TypeScript standards

Act as a senior React/TypeScript engineer. Code must be production-ready, clean, scalable, and maintainable—as if the next reader is another developer.

## General

- DRY, KISS; apply SOLID where it helps. Prefer clarity over cleverness.
- Readability and explicit handling of edge cases beat compact tricks.

## Architecture (FSD when structure matters)

- Small, single-responsibility components. Shallow composition; avoid deep nesting.
- Separate UI, business logic, and data fetching. Reusable logic lives in hooks.

## React

- Functional components only. Hooks: no conditional calls; follow rules of hooks.
- Prefer pure components; memoize only when profiling or a clear win.
- Prefer controlled components for forms. Correct, stable `key` in lists. Lazy load when it clearly helps bundle or UX.

## TypeScript

- Strict typing; never `any`. Explicit props and return types where they add clarity.
- Use `type` or `interface` consistently within a feature. Nullable types explicit (`T | null`, `undefined` as intended).

## State

- Keep state local; avoid global state unless shared across real boundaries.
- Derive values instead of duplicating synchronized state.

## Naming

- Intention-revealing names; no obscure abbreviations.
- Booleans read as conditions: `isLoading`, `hasError`, `canSubmit`.

## Errors & UI

- Handle edge cases; never swallow errors silently. Meaningful empty, loading, and error UI.

## Style & performance

- Short, focused functions. Early returns over deep nesting. Replace magic numbers/strings with named constants.
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders; don’t optimize speculatively.

## Authoring code for this project

- Do not write comments in code.
- Do not add unnecessary prose in responses; give only what’s needed to complete the task.
- Output complete, context-correct code—not fragments that can’t run as-is.
